Prediction For Bike Sharing Demand in Seoul¶

Doukan E. Trkz

In an article [*] featured in the "Computer Communications" journal, the authors considered data for bike sharing demand in Seoul. The data includes weather information (Temperature, Humidity, Windspeed, Visibility, Dewpoint, Solar radiation, Snowfall, Rainfall), the number of bikes rented per hour and date information. We will work with an already preprocessed version of the original dataset and attempt to predict bike demand using a linear regression model, a decision tree regressor model, and a random forest regressor model respectively.

[*] Sathishkumar V E, Jangwoo Park, Yongyun Cho. 'Using data mining techniques for bike sharing demand prediction in metropolitan city.' Computer Communications, Vol.153, pp.353-366, March, 2020. link.

A tad bit of preprocessing¶

We will use a standard scaler to prepare the data for modeling. StandardScaler standardizes all features and scales them to a variance of 1.

In [10]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df)

We now partition the dataframe into the features matrix and the target vector.

In [11]:
X = df.drop(rents, axis=1)
y = df[rents]

We will use 75 % of the data for training our model and the rest for testing.

In [12]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25)

Linear Regression¶

We will first try a linear regression model.

In [13]:
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

By plotting histograms of the test set and our predictions, we see that the linear model does not perform well.

In [14]:
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.hist(y_test, bins=31, label="true", edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.hist(y_pred, bins=31, label="predicion", alpha = 0.75, edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel(rents)
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

To test the performance of the model the following performance assessment indices will be used:

In [15]:
print("R-squared:", (r2_score(y_test, y_pred)))
print("MAE:",(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)))
print("RMSE:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared = False))

R-squared: 0.4564260955736187
MAE: 342.1066119808671
RMSE: 466.72013750783873

We could try to improve our linear regressor model by tuning it; however, it is clear that the data does not follow a linear relationship.

Decision Tree Regressor¶

We now try a decision tree regressor. Since decision trees support non-linearity, we hope for a more accurate model.

In [16]:
model2 = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=2022)
model2.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred2 = model2.predict(X_test)

print("R-squared:", (r2_score(y_test, y_pred2)))
print("MAE:",(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred2)))
print("RMSE:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred2, squared = False))

R-squared: 0.5486165431265118
MAE: 241.5
RMSE: 425.3045796923028

We see that the decision tree regressor model performs better than the linear model, but there is still some room for improvement. We can implement a simple grid search with cross validation (=3) for hyperparameter tuning.

In [17]:
dectr = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=2022)
dectr_par = {"max_depth":np.arange(1,11),"min_samples_leaf":np.arange(2,21)}
grid_dectr = GridSearchCV(dectr,dectr_par,cv=3)
grid_dectr.fit(X_train,y_train)
dectr_bpar = grid_dectr.best_params_
print(dectr_bpar)

{'max_depth': 10, 'min_samples_leaf': 20}

We now train a decision tree regressor model using these parameters.

In [18]:
dtr=DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=dectr_bpar['max_depth'],min_samples_leaf= dectr_bpar["min_samples_leaf"])
model2 = dtr.fit(X_train,y_train)
y_pred2 = model2.predict(X_test)

We use the same metrics to test the tuned decision tree regressor model.

In [19]:
print("R-squared:", (r2_score(y_test, y_pred2)))
print("MAE:",(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred2)))
print("RMSE:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred2, squared = False))

R-squared: 0.6864674735211127
MAE: 223.1876974465779
RMSE: 354.4610675693895

We see that the R-Squared value increased while MAE and RMSE both decreased. This indicates that the decision tree regressor model seems to perform better than the linear model.

Plotting histograms of the test set and our predictions also agrees with the improvements of the model.

In [20]:
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.hist(y_test, bins=31, label="true", edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.hist(y_pred2, bins=31, label="predicion", alpha = 0.75, edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel(rents)
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

Random Forest Regressor¶

Lastly, we train a random forest regressor.

In [21]:
model3 = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=2022)
model3.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred3 = model3.predict(X_test)
In [22]:
print("R-squared:", (r2_score(y_test, y_pred3)))
print("MAE:",(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred3)))
print("RMSE:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred3, squared = False))

R-squared: 0.7588078220662864
MAE: 186.6739311594203
RMSE: 310.8915010229989

The random forest regressor seems to give the best performance according to the metrics we used. This can also be seen by plotting the histograms of the test set and our predictions.

In [23]:
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.hist(y_test, bins=31, label="true", edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.hist(y_pred3, bins=31, label="predicion", alpha = 0.75, edgecolor = 'dimgray')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel(rents)
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

We define the residual as the difference between the true values and the values predicted by the model. From the scatter plot the residual seems to be high for early morning hours and for certain data points having a rented bike count of 0 (although these differ slighly in each run due to the stochastic nature of the model).

In [24]:
resid = y_test - y_pred3
In [25]:
figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.scatter(y_test, resid, c = X_test['Hour'], cmap = 'seismic')
plt.colorbar()
plt.xlabel("Rented Bike Count")
plt.ylabel("Residual")
plt.title("Residual vs. Rented Bike Count with Hour Shown by Color", fontsize=14)
plt.show()
